WEBVTT

00:01.751 --> 00:02.668
<i>- A brilliant safecracker...</i>

00:02.752 --> 00:04.661
- He spoke five languages.

00:04.746 --> 00:06.413
<i>- Locked up in
a dangerous prison</i>

00:06.497 --> 00:09.174
<i>nicknamed "The Wall."</i>

00:09.259 --> 00:11.084
- It was only a matter of time
until I either got killed,

00:11.169 --> 00:12.344
or killed somebody.

00:12.503 --> 00:15.756
<i>- Hand picks a team of
five hardened convicts.</i>

00:15.849 --> 00:18.341
- There was certainly a risk
to add additional members.

00:18.426 --> 00:20.343
<i>- To tunnel out of the prison.</i>

00:20.428 --> 00:22.512
- If the tunnel was collapsing,
that would shut off

00:22.597 --> 00:24.606
the air supply.

00:24.766 --> 00:26.433
<i>- And make their way to freedom.</i>

00:26.526 --> 00:27.768
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:27.861 --> 00:29.778
<i>- If they was found out
digging that tunnel,</i>

00:29.863 --> 00:31.363
they would have went to the
Hole for a lot of years.

00:31.522 --> 00:38.370
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:40.948 --> 00:43.617
<i>[exciting music]</i>

00:43.701 --> 00:46.453
- Some of
the greatest stories ever told

00:46.546 --> 00:50.049
start behind bars.

00:50.208 --> 00:52.217
<i>Locked up in the most
notorious prisons</i>

00:52.376 --> 00:55.796
<i>in the world, spied on by guards</i>

00:55.880 --> 00:58.390
<i>and fellow prisoners,</i>

00:58.549 --> 01:03.812
<i>it takes a devious mind
to find a way out.</i>

01:03.971 --> 01:06.389
<i>It could lead you to freedom,</i>

01:06.483 --> 01:09.059
<i>or it could cost you your life.</i>

01:09.143 --> 01:10.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:10.737 --> 01:13.155
<i>But wouldn't you try</i>

01:13.314 --> 01:14.740
when you have
nothing left to lose?

01:14.899 --> 01:21.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:21.823 --> 01:27.327
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

01:27.411 --> 01:29.671
<i>- Western Penitentiary,</i>

01:29.831 --> 01:32.582
<i>Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.</i>

01:32.667 --> 01:37.254
Freezing cold in winter,
boiling hot in summer.

01:37.347 --> 01:40.423
Sometimes it floods here too.

01:40.508 --> 01:44.269
It's one of
the oldest prisons in America.

01:44.428 --> 01:48.774
Back in 1882, its
amenities were cutting edge;

01:48.933 --> 01:52.361
running water, electricity,
and common spaces

01:52.520 --> 01:55.105
for prisoners to congregate.

01:55.198 --> 01:57.950
<i>But what began
as an enlightened experiment</i>

01:58.109 --> 02:02.621
<i>in criminal reform
became a living hell.</i>

02:02.780 --> 02:08.785
By 1996, it was overcrowded
and in disrepair.

02:08.870 --> 02:11.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:11.289 --> 02:16.301
The one thing that never
changed is its nickname,

02:16.460 --> 02:17.878
"the Wall."

02:17.962 --> 02:23.300
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:23.393 --> 02:25.886
<i>- The walls
of Western State Penitentiary</i>

02:25.970 --> 02:29.973
<i>are very large, very forbidding,</i>

02:30.057 --> 02:36.229
very fortress-like, massive
stone and concrete walls.

02:36.314 --> 02:38.398
<i>They're 25 feet tall.</i>

02:38.482 --> 02:41.160
<i>They also run underground.</i>

02:41.319 --> 02:44.163
<i>- Your security perimeter,
that's level one</i>

02:44.322 --> 02:46.665
<i>to deter escapes.</i>

02:46.824 --> 02:50.327
<i>Then, inside the perimeter,
your gates,</i>

02:50.411 --> 02:52.162
<i>doors on the cellblocks,</i>

02:52.246 --> 02:54.840
all those things
that deter inmate movement

02:54.999 --> 02:58.677
<i>are part of the system
that keeps people in.</i>

02:58.836 --> 03:03.015
- Where most people see a
series of impossible obstacles,

03:03.174 --> 03:06.185
one man sees a puzzle
to be solved.

03:06.344 --> 03:13.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:13.109 --> 03:16.019
<i>He's never told
his story on camera</i>

03:16.112 --> 03:17.196
until now.

03:17.355 --> 03:23.610
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:23.703 --> 03:26.872
- The reason why I don't want
my face seen is because

03:26.956 --> 03:31.368
I'd like to have the option of
choosing who I let know.

03:31.452 --> 03:33.703
The fact is,
that once you get that label

03:33.788 --> 03:37.299
of criminal, that can lead
to discrimination.

03:37.458 --> 03:40.627
<i>- By 1996,
Nuno Pontes is serving</i>

03:40.711 --> 03:43.722
<i>a 10-to 24-year sentence
for safecracking.</i>

03:43.881 --> 03:45.557
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:45.716 --> 03:46.892
<i>He's a Robin Hood,</i>

03:47.051 --> 03:50.136
<i>stealing from the rich
and giving to the poor,</i>

03:50.221 --> 03:52.314
<i>as well as to himself.</i>

03:52.473 --> 03:56.735
<i>Over the last decade, he has
been in and out of prison.</i>

03:56.894 --> 03:59.396
<i>He's been at Western Pen
for the past four years,</i>

03:59.480 --> 04:01.406
<i>and, for the first time,</i>

04:01.565 --> 04:05.911
<i>he just happens to have
a cellmate he can trust.</i>

04:06.070 --> 04:12.409
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:12.502 --> 04:15.754
- I became cellmates with Nuno
in '96,

04:15.838 --> 04:17.497
or end of '95.

04:17.590 --> 04:19.758
<i>I call Nuno, "Nick."</i>

04:19.917 --> 04:23.428
<i>He's articulate, passionate,
he's brave.</i>

04:23.587 --> 04:25.847
He believes what he says,
and he backs it up.

04:26.007 --> 04:28.591
<i>Those dudes are a rare breed.</i>

04:28.676 --> 04:31.270
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:31.429 --> 04:33.680
- Because of my nature,
I had been thinking

04:33.764 --> 04:35.348
about escaping all along.

04:35.433 --> 04:37.434
There was nothing positive
to do,

04:37.518 --> 04:40.603
and the penitentiary
was just too dangerous.

04:40.697 --> 04:42.447
- It was definitely
a dangerous place.

04:42.606 --> 04:45.358
One time, I saw three guys
were stabbing this other guy.

04:45.451 --> 04:47.035
I don't know what it was about,
I don't want to know

04:47.194 --> 04:50.205
what it was about.
He ended up dying.

04:50.290 --> 04:51.957
Raises the stakes
is what it does.

04:52.116 --> 04:54.534
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:54.627 --> 04:56.953
- It was only a matter of time
until I either got killed,

04:57.046 --> 04:58.788
or killed somebody
out of necessity.

04:58.873 --> 05:01.875
And either one of those
was an unacceptable option,

05:01.959 --> 05:03.135
<i>so I decided to leave.</i>

05:03.294 --> 05:10.216
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:10.310 --> 05:12.135
<i>- Nuno begins brainstorming</i>

05:12.219 --> 05:14.313
<i>with his cellmate about how
someone could escape</i>

05:14.397 --> 05:16.481
<i>the prison.</i>

05:16.640 --> 05:19.067
<i>- The first option
that I considered was</i>

05:19.226 --> 05:21.644
<i>actually bringing the wall down.</i>

05:21.729 --> 05:24.397
That was abandoned because they
would have known right away

05:24.482 --> 05:25.907
that there was a mistake.

05:26.067 --> 05:27.317
<i>- Their next idea</i>

05:27.401 --> 05:29.995
<i>is to hide
in a construction truck,</i>

05:30.154 --> 05:34.157
<i>but they soon realize
that's a dead end.</i>

05:34.250 --> 05:36.335
<i>There's always
a prisoner headcount</i>

05:36.494 --> 05:38.170
<i>before any truck leaves
the compound.</i>

05:38.329 --> 05:39.662
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:39.756 --> 05:40.914
<i>- Then we came
to the third option,</i>

05:40.998 --> 05:41.915
which was a tunnel.

05:41.999 --> 05:43.333
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:43.417 --> 05:45.418
<i>- Over the last hundred years,</i>

05:45.511 --> 05:49.014
<i>many prisoners have attempted
to escape this hellhole</i>

05:49.173 --> 05:51.600
<i>by tunneling out.</i>

05:51.759 --> 05:54.019
<i>But none have been successful.</i>

05:54.178 --> 05:56.429
<i>Not yet.</i>

05:56.522 --> 06:01.684
<i>Nuno thinks he can succeed,
but he can't do it alone.</i>

06:01.778 --> 06:04.112
<i>He has no experience tunneling,</i>

06:04.271 --> 06:06.198
<i>and neither does his cellmate.</i>

06:06.282 --> 06:08.858
- That's when Arizona became
interesting, I think.

06:08.951 --> 06:10.619
Billingsley's nickname
was Arizona

06:10.778 --> 06:12.162
because he was from Arizona.

06:14.365 --> 06:17.367
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:17.460 --> 06:19.711
<i>- Kevin Billingsley is serving</i>

06:19.796 --> 06:23.465
<i>a 23 1/2-to 77-year sentence
for several charges,</i>

06:23.624 --> 06:26.468
<i>including robbery and assault.</i>

06:26.552 --> 06:27.794
[siren wails]

06:27.887 --> 06:32.048
<i>And he has skills Nuno needs
to dig a tunnel.</i>

06:32.133 --> 06:34.559
<i>- I meet Kevin Billingsley
through an old convict.</i>

06:34.644 --> 06:37.479
<i>I made introductions
because Kevin also was</i>

06:37.638 --> 06:39.731
<i>pursuing the idea of an escape.</i>

06:39.816 --> 06:41.141
[rattling]

06:41.234 --> 06:43.726
<i>Kevin had, actually,
some mining experience,</i>

06:43.811 --> 06:45.145
<i>but he was very skeptical.</i>

06:45.238 --> 06:47.739
<i>And my idea was, we'll just
break the process down</i>

06:47.824 --> 06:48.982
<i>into stages.</i>

06:49.066 --> 06:51.151
We'll tackle one stage
at a time.

06:51.235 --> 06:54.154
<i>- With Kevin Billingsley
on board,</i>

06:54.247 --> 06:57.666
<i>the next step is to determine
where the three of them</i>

06:57.750 --> 06:59.909
<i>should dig.</i>

06:59.994 --> 07:02.412
<i>The only way to do that
is to get jobs</i>

07:02.496 --> 07:04.581
<i>that will give them more access</i>

07:04.665 --> 07:07.917
<i>and knowledge
of the prison's layout.</i>

07:08.002 --> 07:12.180
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:12.265 --> 07:15.091
<i>Nuno Pontes sets his sights
on working</i>

07:15.176 --> 07:16.176
<i>with the prison engineer</i>

07:16.269 --> 07:19.095
<i>in the prison's
maintenance office.</i>

07:19.180 --> 07:22.182
- The prison engineer
is a critical person.

07:22.275 --> 07:26.769
He or she was responsible for
the plumbing, the sewage,

07:26.863 --> 07:29.189
<i>the electrical, the ventilation.</i>

07:29.273 --> 07:32.951
And his office was
the repository

07:33.035 --> 07:36.121
for all of the blueprints.

07:36.280 --> 07:43.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:43.296 --> 07:45.371
<i>- With a job in maintenance,</i>

07:45.465 --> 07:50.302
<i>Nuno now has an inside view
of how this place works.</i>

07:50.386 --> 07:53.129
<i>- I had access to
all the maintenance issues.</i>

07:53.222 --> 07:55.390
Through that, I collected
quite a bit of knowledge

07:55.549 --> 07:57.634
about how the institution
was set up.

07:57.718 --> 08:00.145
<i>[clock ticking]</i>

08:00.304 --> 08:05.725
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:05.809 --> 08:08.645
<i>- And by
a remarkable stroke of luck,</i>

08:08.729 --> 08:11.323
<i>Nuno receives a request
to fix a problem</i>

08:11.407 --> 08:16.069
<i>in a warehouse just outside
the prison perimeter.</i>

08:16.153 --> 08:19.155
<i>This might be the place</i>

08:19.248 --> 08:21.833
<i>where the tunnel could end.</i>

08:21.992 --> 08:23.168
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:23.327 --> 08:26.171
<i>- The institutional warehouse,
it's function is</i>

08:26.255 --> 08:30.083
to control the movement
of goods and products

08:30.167 --> 08:34.179
<i>into the prison from the street.</i>

08:34.338 --> 08:36.598
<i>- Nuno knows
that if they can find a way</i>

08:36.682 --> 08:39.759
<i>into that warehouse,
they can then walk</i>

08:39.843 --> 08:40.852
<i>right onto the street.</i>

08:41.011 --> 08:42.262
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:42.355 --> 08:45.023
<i>It's the perfect exit point
for their tunnel.</i>

08:45.182 --> 08:46.849
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:46.934 --> 08:50.612
<i>But he still needs to find
where it should start,</i>

08:50.696 --> 08:55.024
<i>a spot he and his co-escapees
can access</i>

08:55.117 --> 08:58.945
<i>away from the watchful eyes
of the guards.</i>

08:59.029 --> 09:02.448
<i>Nuno starts eyeing a secluded
part of the maintenance shops</i>

09:02.533 --> 09:07.537
<i>close to the warehouse
on the other side of the wall.</i>

09:07.630 --> 09:10.048
- The maintenance office
and the maintenance shops

09:10.132 --> 09:13.885
<i>are built just inside
the perimeter wall.</i>

09:14.044 --> 09:18.381
<i>They are close to opposite
the institutional warehouse,</i>

09:18.474 --> 09:21.393
<i>which is on the exterior
of the wall.</i>

09:21.477 --> 09:23.979
<i>- Nuno is eventually
able to get his hands</i>

09:24.138 --> 09:26.973
<i>on blueprints of the building.</i>

09:27.057 --> 09:31.060
<i>Using these diagrams,
he determines the perfect spot</i>

09:31.145 --> 09:35.898
<i>to start digging the tunnel
is this crawl space.</i>

09:35.983 --> 09:39.244
<i>But the place is surrounded
by impenetrable brick walls</i>

09:39.403 --> 09:41.913
<i>and a steel door.</i>

09:42.072 --> 09:45.750
<i>Somehow, they have
to get past all this.</i>

09:45.909 --> 09:49.754
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:49.839 --> 09:53.008
<i>Thinking it over, something
suddenly occurs to him.</i>

09:53.092 --> 09:56.836
<i>He can access the crawl space
if he can drill through</i>

09:56.920 --> 09:59.848
<i>its exterior brick wall.</i>

10:00.007 --> 10:02.934
<i>And he knows exactly the spot.</i>

10:03.019 --> 10:06.346
<i>- So, to get through this wall
that led to the crawl space,</i>

10:06.439 --> 10:10.358
I broke this overflow pipe
for this steam tank.

10:10.517 --> 10:11.851
And I told the maintenance guy,

10:11.935 --> 10:13.770
I said, "Hey, there's this
steam tank that's leaking,

10:13.854 --> 10:17.440
but if you guys get me
a hammer drill, I'll fix it."

10:17.533 --> 10:19.609
<i>So security came over
and approved the job</i>

10:19.702 --> 10:21.036
<i>and brought
this hammer drill in.</i>

10:21.195 --> 10:22.704
<i>They stood there with me.</i>

10:22.863 --> 10:26.949
<i>I crawled under this platform,
started drilling on the wall.</i>

10:27.034 --> 10:28.126
<i>Of course,
the guard now is talking,</i>

10:28.285 --> 10:30.453
<i>so I would drill
a little bit on this wall</i>

10:30.537 --> 10:32.455
<i>and then go to the wall I
actually wanted to go through,</i>

10:32.539 --> 10:34.290
<i>and drill on that one.</i>

10:34.375 --> 10:37.293
<i>- Nuno was attempting
to access the crawl space</i>

10:37.378 --> 10:41.723
<i>with a guard standing
right next to him.</i>

10:41.882 --> 10:42.974
<i>It's a bold plan.</i>

10:43.059 --> 10:44.967
[drill whines]

10:45.052 --> 10:48.638
<i>If the officer figures out
what he's up to,</i>

10:48.722 --> 10:51.974
<i>the plot to escape this dank
and dangerous prison</i>

10:52.068 --> 10:54.319
<i>will be over
before it even begins.</i>

10:54.478 --> 10:57.447
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:01.661 --> 11:04.570
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:04.655 --> 11:07.082
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:07.241 --> 11:09.158
- At Pittsburg's notorious

11:09.243 --> 11:14.172
Western Penitentiary,
Nuno Pontes is trying to drill

11:14.331 --> 11:18.501
his way into
an underground crawl space.

11:18.585 --> 11:21.179
From there,
he'll be able to tunnel

11:21.338 --> 11:23.515
under the prison's
impenetrable wall.

11:23.599 --> 11:24.849
[drill whines]

11:24.934 --> 11:29.437
Right now, however,
he's being watched closely.

11:29.522 --> 11:32.432
But every time
the guard looks away,

11:32.516 --> 11:36.861
Nuno shifts his focus
to the crawl space wall,

11:36.946 --> 11:41.858
trying to break down
the first barrier between him

11:41.942 --> 11:42.784
and freedom.

11:42.868 --> 11:44.610
<i>[drill whines]</i>

11:44.695 --> 11:46.112
- It was just taking too long.

11:46.205 --> 11:48.373
This drill didn't have enough
oomph to get into that area

11:48.457 --> 11:52.869
<i>to dig.
And then we abandoned that.</i>

11:52.953 --> 11:55.121
<i>- Since he can't
get into the crawl space</i>

11:55.205 --> 11:58.216
<i>with a drill, Nuno Pontes,
Kevin Billingsley,</i>

11:58.300 --> 12:03.555
<i>and Greg Quiring are going to
have to find another way.</i>

12:03.639 --> 12:06.641
- The second option was
to make a key

12:06.800 --> 12:10.136
and go through the actual doors
that led to the crawl space.

12:10.220 --> 12:16.058
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:16.143 --> 12:19.487
<i>- The three escapees need a key,</i>

12:19.572 --> 12:22.741
<i>a key only the guards have,</i>

12:22.825 --> 12:27.746
<i>and, somehow, they have
to find a way to make a copy.</i>

12:27.905 --> 12:29.247
<i>- Just weren't sure
what we could use</i>

12:29.331 --> 12:31.741
<i>that would hold
the form of the key.</i>

12:31.834 --> 12:33.501
This has got to be a good print.

12:33.586 --> 12:36.913
<i>It's got to be both sides
for this key to work.</i>

12:36.997 --> 12:39.841
- We experimented
with various materials.

12:39.925 --> 12:42.418
'Cause, obviously, we needed
to get an imprint of the key.

12:42.503 --> 12:44.846
<i>- I know we tried a bar of soap,</i>

12:44.930 --> 12:50.092
<i>and then we did oatmeal,
and then it was Styrofoam.</i>

12:50.177 --> 12:53.179
The Styrofoam really, you know,
held a nice imprint.

12:53.263 --> 12:55.848
<i>- Once they get
an impression of the key,</i>

12:55.941 --> 12:59.277
<i>they can then transfer that
to a piece of paper.</i>

12:59.361 --> 13:02.030
<i>- Then, from the piece of
paper, we made a key blank,</i>

13:02.189 --> 13:03.364
<i>you know, out of brass.</i>

13:03.449 --> 13:05.116
<i>In the machine shop,
we cut a piece of brass</i>

13:05.275 --> 13:07.276
the right size,
and then just transferred

13:07.369 --> 13:11.531
the shape of the key onto it.

13:11.624 --> 13:13.533
<i>- Now they need
to get their hands on the key</i>

13:13.626 --> 13:15.201
<i>to the door.</i>

13:15.285 --> 13:17.462
<i>But how?</i>

13:17.546 --> 13:20.540
<i>- So we waited for the guards
to do their rounds.</i>

13:20.624 --> 13:22.383
<i>Once they opened the lock,</i>

13:22.468 --> 13:25.378
<i>they put the keys
back on their belt.</i>

13:25.471 --> 13:28.714
<i>But the key they just used
tends to be on top.</i>

13:28.808 --> 13:30.475
<i>Obviously, the guard is not
gonna be too keen</i>

13:30.559 --> 13:32.477
<i>to let you approach him
close enough</i>

13:32.636 --> 13:33.561
<i>for you to get
an imprint of the key.</i>

13:33.646 --> 13:35.054
<i>- They have an idea.</i>

13:35.147 --> 13:36.564
[people shouting]

13:36.649 --> 13:41.060
<i>Nuno pays two inmates
to create a diversion for him.</i>

13:41.153 --> 13:45.573
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:45.732 --> 13:48.660
<i>- The guard has to intervene,
but as the guard tries</i>

13:48.744 --> 13:50.903
to diffuse the situation,
I step in.

13:50.988 --> 13:52.747
And he's welcoming
the fact that I'm there

13:52.832 --> 13:54.666
and I'm helping
to quell the thing.

13:54.825 --> 13:56.325
<i>But I'm sitting
right next to him.</i>

13:56.410 --> 13:57.669
<i>I mean,
we are shoulder to shoulder.</i>

13:57.828 --> 14:00.913
<i>And that gives me
the opportunity to reach down.</i>

14:00.998 --> 14:02.257
<i>- Nuno has mere seconds</i>

14:02.416 --> 14:04.000
<i>to make the impression,</i>

14:04.084 --> 14:05.501
<i>and the clock is ticking.</i>

14:05.586 --> 14:08.763
<i>- It's a tense situation.</i>

14:08.848 --> 14:11.257
<i>My concern was that
the guard would hear the keys</i>

14:11.341 --> 14:12.425
<i>as I touched them.</i>

14:12.518 --> 14:14.519
[keys jingle]

14:14.678 --> 14:15.928
It actually worked
and went fairly smoothly.

14:16.013 --> 14:21.017
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:21.101 --> 14:23.102
<i>- With the key print in hand,</i>

14:23.186 --> 14:25.438
<i>he can have a key made.</i>

14:25.531 --> 14:28.032
<i>And Kevin Billingsley
does that at night</i>

14:28.117 --> 14:30.860
<i>in his cell
in between the guards' rounds.</i>

14:30.944 --> 14:33.279
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:33.372 --> 14:36.291
<i>The next step is to try
the key they've just made</i>

14:36.375 --> 14:39.535
<i>to see if it works.</i>

14:39.620 --> 14:43.047
<i>And they must do it
without being detected.</i>

14:43.132 --> 14:45.708
- There's a risk that
one of the guard towers

14:45.792 --> 14:47.293
would be able to see them.

14:47.377 --> 14:49.387
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:49.546 --> 14:51.714
<i>- Nuno knows
from observing the guards</i>

14:51.798 --> 14:55.801
<i>that he and Greg have exactly
17 seconds to get to the door</i>

14:55.895 --> 14:57.562
<i>and try the key</i>

14:57.721 --> 15:00.222
<i>before the guard
on the wall above them</i>

15:00.307 --> 15:03.476
<i>comes out of his booth
and sees them at the door</i>

15:03.560 --> 15:06.729
<i>where they shouldn't be.</i>

15:06.813 --> 15:09.732
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:09.816 --> 15:14.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:14.747 --> 15:16.664
- We went down, we were
going to go check the key,

15:16.823 --> 15:17.907
make sure it works.

15:17.991 --> 15:24.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:29.086 --> 15:31.596
Made it too thin. It broke.

15:31.680 --> 15:34.590
<i>- Amazingly,
the guard in the tower</i>

15:34.675 --> 15:38.511
<i>doesn't see them, and he won't
be able to see the broken key.</i>

15:38.595 --> 15:41.773
<i>But they aren't in the clear.</i>

15:41.932 --> 15:44.609
<i>- There would be checks
that would come around</i>

15:44.693 --> 15:46.686
to check to make sure that
that lock is locked.

15:46.770 --> 15:49.197
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:49.356 --> 15:51.282
<i>- If the key is found,</i>

15:51.441 --> 15:54.702
<i>not only will their plan
be discovered,</i>

15:54.861 --> 15:58.698
<i>they'll also be sent to the
place every prisoner dreads.</i>

15:58.782 --> 16:00.208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:00.367 --> 16:04.212
<i>Solitary confinement.</i>

16:04.296 --> 16:06.631
- It was a question of
coming up with ways of dealing

16:06.715 --> 16:07.882
with unpredictable events.

16:08.041 --> 16:11.552
I had to deal with
those situations on the fly.

16:11.712 --> 16:14.964
<i>- Their only option is
to steal needle-nose pliers</i>

16:15.048 --> 16:17.049
<i>from Nuno's job
at the maintenance office</i>

16:17.134 --> 16:20.812
<i>on the back side
of the building.</i>

16:20.971 --> 16:23.639
<i>- Pontes knew where tools were.</i>

16:23.724 --> 16:25.141
<i>He was able to get
to this cabinet</i>

16:25.225 --> 16:26.651
<i>where the tools were kept,</i>

16:26.735 --> 16:29.487
file the hinge pins off
on the bottom,

16:29.646 --> 16:33.408
pop the hinge pins out,
take the tools,

16:33.492 --> 16:35.484
<i>put the hinge pins back in,</i>

16:35.569 --> 16:39.238
and then get them back
at the end of the day.

16:39.331 --> 16:42.575
<i>- His heart races
as he rushes back to the lock</i>

16:42.659 --> 16:45.336
<i>with the stolen pliers,</i>

16:45.421 --> 16:48.840
<i>hoping the guard in the tower
doesn't see him.</i>

16:48.924 --> 16:53.094
<i>And if he can't get the
broken key out of the lock,</i>

16:53.253 --> 16:57.598
<i>it will be just a matter of
time before they are caught.</i>

16:57.758 --> 17:01.427
<i>At last, it's out.</i>

17:01.511 --> 17:05.264
<i>But they still don't have
a working key.</i>

17:05.348 --> 17:07.191
<i>- It wasn't just
a one-try thing.</i>

17:07.276 --> 17:08.776
I actually had to go
several times

17:08.861 --> 17:10.862
until I got the key adjusted.

17:11.021 --> 17:14.356
<i>- And then we got
another key made.</i>

17:14.441 --> 17:18.110
<i>- This is the moment
they have been waiting for.</i>

17:18.195 --> 17:22.448
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:22.541 --> 17:25.785
[lock clicks]

17:25.878 --> 17:27.620
- And it worked.

17:27.704 --> 17:30.298
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:30.457 --> 17:33.134
- The first time that it works,
relief is the main emotion.

17:33.293 --> 17:36.387
It's like, whew, finally.

17:36.546 --> 17:38.798
<i>- They can now
access the crawl space</i>

17:38.882 --> 17:40.892
<i>to begin digging.</i>

17:40.976 --> 17:44.553
<i>But before they start
operating full speed ahead,</i>

17:44.638 --> 17:47.389
<i>they need to divert
the attention of the guards</i>

17:47.474 --> 17:50.476
<i>away from the digging operation.</i>

17:50.560 --> 17:56.491
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:56.575 --> 18:01.403
<i>- So my idea was the standard
strategy magicians use.</i>

18:01.497 --> 18:03.155
You show one thing
with one hand,

18:03.240 --> 18:05.416
as you're doing one thing
with the other hand.

18:05.575 --> 18:09.411
So what I decide to do
is to mount a huge

18:09.496 --> 18:12.256
<i>wine-producing operation.</i>

18:12.415 --> 18:15.510
<i>We were making 30 gallons
at a time.</i>

18:15.594 --> 18:18.763
<i>We are actually taking,
you know, gallons of wine</i>

18:18.922 --> 18:21.257
<i>out to the yard
and have lines set up.</i>

18:21.341 --> 18:26.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:26.847 --> 18:28.848
<i>- The guard become focused
on trying to nab</i>

18:28.932 --> 18:30.942
<i>their wine-making operation,</i>

18:31.026 --> 18:33.861
<i>not realizing that the trio
is getting ready to start</i>

18:33.946 --> 18:35.363
<i>digging the tunnel.</i>

18:35.447 --> 18:37.949
<i>They're waiting
for them to slip up.</i>

18:38.108 --> 18:41.944
<i>Nuno's magic trick is
a dangerous proposition</i>

18:42.028 --> 18:43.696
<i>because if they're caught,</i>

18:43.780 --> 18:46.699
<i>their whole escape plan
could be in jeopardy.</i>

18:46.783 --> 18:50.202
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:50.287 --> 18:51.629
<i>- There was this one guard
in particular</i>

18:51.788 --> 18:53.631
<i>that used to be
in the gate when I came</i>

18:53.715 --> 18:55.958
<i>from work to go back
to the block.</i>

18:56.042 --> 18:57.543
<i>He really didn't like me.</i>

18:57.627 --> 18:59.470
<i>One time, I got to the gate,
and he says,</i>

18:59.629 --> 19:01.973
<i>"Pontes, put your hands up.
Pat-down."</i>

19:02.132 --> 19:04.049
<i>So I pull my keys
out of my pocket</i>

19:04.134 --> 19:05.810
<i>and hand them to one guard,
and I say,</i>

19:05.894 --> 19:07.303
<i>here, hold these.</i>

19:07.387 --> 19:10.472
- Inmates do have certain keys
they're allowed to have.

19:10.557 --> 19:12.900
<i>A padlock on a footlocker,
for instance.</i>

19:12.985 --> 19:16.487
- But in my keys, I also had
the keys that were their keys.

19:16.572 --> 19:18.156
I had these keys that,
obviously, they weren't

19:18.240 --> 19:19.899
the type of keys
inmates would have.

19:19.983 --> 19:21.909
<i>- Nuno has just handed
the guard the keys</i>

19:21.994 --> 19:24.486
<i>to his escape.</i>

19:24.571 --> 19:27.582
<i>Will the guard uncover his plans</i>

19:27.666 --> 19:31.410
<i>and keep him trapped
in this hellhole forever?</i>

19:31.503 --> 19:33.171
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:37.926 --> 19:39.585
- As he plots his escape

19:39.678 --> 19:43.839
from a Pittsburg prison,
Nuno Pontes is about to get

19:43.924 --> 19:47.351
a pat-down search
from a prison guard.

19:47.510 --> 19:51.013
The one thing Nuno does not
want him to find

19:51.097 --> 19:55.860
is the illegal copy
of the key to the crawl space.

19:55.944 --> 19:59.197
That is the key to his freedom,

19:59.281 --> 20:02.533
so he makes a bold choice.

20:02.618 --> 20:05.527
He hands the key
right to the guard.

20:05.612 --> 20:07.947
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:08.031 --> 20:09.531
<i>- They never actually looked
at the keys.</i>

20:09.616 --> 20:15.880
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:16.039 --> 20:18.299
<i>- While Nuno may
not have gotten caught</i>

20:18.383 --> 20:20.134
<i>with the keys
to the crawl space,</i>

20:20.219 --> 20:23.221
<i>their wine-making operation
backfires.</i>

20:23.380 --> 20:26.048
<i>They lose
one of their team members,</i>

20:26.132 --> 20:28.142
<i>Greg Quiring.</i>

20:28.227 --> 20:30.719
- I was on cell restriction
for the wine. [chuckles]

20:30.812 --> 20:32.304
So I was locked in my cell.

20:32.389 --> 20:34.556
<i>I can't be at yard,
I can't be at work</i>

20:34.641 --> 20:36.392
<i>at the library or anything else.</i>

20:36.485 --> 20:39.478
<i>- After his time
on cell restriction,</i>

20:39.571 --> 20:43.407
<i>Greg is sent to solitary
for an unrelated incident.</i>

20:43.566 --> 20:45.993
<i>He won't be taking part
in the escape.</i>

20:46.152 --> 20:48.412
<i>Luckily for the team,</i>

20:48.497 --> 20:52.157
<i>Greg is the only one nabbed
for wine-making.</i>

20:52.242 --> 20:57.672
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:57.756 --> 20:59.581
<i>With the precarious cover
in place</i>

20:59.666 --> 21:01.667
<i>and the key to the crawl space,</i>

21:01.751 --> 21:04.920
<i>Nuno and Kevin are ready
to start digging.</i>

21:05.005 --> 21:08.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:08.517 --> 21:10.759
<i>- At first,
it was just Kevin and I.</i>

21:10.852 --> 21:12.761
And we would take turns
going down there

21:12.854 --> 21:14.438
<i>because when we go down to dig,</i>

21:14.523 --> 21:15.690
<i>somebody has to lock</i>

21:15.849 --> 21:16.941
<i>whoever's down there in</i>

21:17.100 --> 21:19.360
<i>'cause you can't
leave the lock unlocked.</i>

21:19.519 --> 21:21.112
<i>The guards would notice.</i>

21:21.271 --> 21:23.689
<i>- Once they're locked
into the crawl space,</i>

21:23.782 --> 21:26.617
<i>they have little more
than some pieces of wood,</i>

21:26.776 --> 21:29.361
<i>some buckets, and some hardhats</i>

21:29.446 --> 21:31.706
<i>they've stolen
from the prison's power plant</i>

21:31.865 --> 21:34.375
<i>and rigged with lights.</i>

21:34.459 --> 21:37.286
- The digging is hard.
The soil is clay.

21:37.370 --> 21:38.454
It's a riverbank.

21:38.538 --> 21:42.458
We would break clay loose
with the sticks

21:42.542 --> 21:46.545
<i>and then pull it up
into the crawl space.</i>

21:46.629 --> 21:50.391
- Just to go 60 feet, they have
to remove 15 tons of soil

21:50.550 --> 21:53.385
from that little opening.

21:53.470 --> 21:54.895
<i>That's a lot of material
to be hauling around.</i>

21:55.055 --> 21:56.147
It's very strenuous.

21:56.231 --> 21:58.232
<i>- Nuno and Kevin are
hoping to tunnel</i>

21:58.317 --> 22:00.142
<i>from the crawl space
to the warehouse</i>

22:00.226 --> 22:03.145
<i>on the other side of the wall,</i>

22:03.229 --> 22:06.991
<i>but there are big obstacles
in their way.</i>

22:07.150 --> 22:08.826
<i>- The wall went
down underground,</i>

22:08.985 --> 22:11.162
<i>so we would have to dig
14 feet down,</i>

22:11.321 --> 22:14.490
<i>and then across
because there was a road</i>

22:14.574 --> 22:16.742
- There's quite a bit
of inherent danger

22:16.826 --> 22:19.337
where they dug this tunnel.

22:19.421 --> 22:23.832
<i>Coal trucks run over the road
that they went underneath.</i>

22:23.917 --> 22:26.844
They certainly had
a real possibility

22:26.928 --> 22:28.087
of having a cave-in.

22:28.171 --> 22:30.431
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:30.590 --> 22:33.425
<i>- And not only do they have to
worry about collapse,</i>

22:33.510 --> 22:36.178
<i>they also have to worry about
running out of oxygen</i>

22:36.262 --> 22:38.105
<i>as they dig deeper
into the earth.</i>

22:38.190 --> 22:40.349
[heavy breathing]

22:40.433 --> 22:44.520
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:44.604 --> 22:46.772
<i>- We were constantly
running out of air in there,</i>

22:46.865 --> 22:49.608
<i>so we have to come back,
turn around, and go back.</i>

22:49.692 --> 22:50.951
<i>- The threat of collapse</i>

22:51.036 --> 22:52.453
<i>and the potential
for suffocating</i>

22:52.612 --> 22:55.030
<i>is heavy on their minds</i>

22:55.115 --> 22:58.534
<i>as they slowly expand
their tunnel.</i>

22:58.627 --> 23:00.211
<i>But the risk is worth the reward</i>

23:00.370 --> 23:02.037
<i>if they can dig
their way to freedom.</i>

23:02.122 --> 23:09.053
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:13.967 --> 23:15.968
<i>The work is slow going.</i>

23:16.061 --> 23:19.138
<i>Nuno and Kevin debate about
adding another team member</i>

23:19.231 --> 23:21.056
<i>to help dig.</i>

23:21.141 --> 23:23.892
<i>Then something
out of their control happens.</i>

23:23.985 --> 23:26.987
- Carmen Keller saw something.

23:27.147 --> 23:28.397
<i>He's asking questions.</i>

23:28.490 --> 23:29.990
<i>He's obviously suspicious
that something more</i>

23:30.075 --> 23:31.984
<i>than just the wine-making
is going on.</i>

23:32.068 --> 23:37.998
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:38.083 --> 23:40.159
<i>- Carmen Keller,
an inmate serving</i>

23:40.243 --> 23:42.420
<i>a life sentence
for second-degree murder,</i>

23:42.579 --> 23:45.840
<i>is added to the team
as a third member.</i>

23:45.999 --> 23:49.343
- I'm nervous about hiring him,
but by bringing him in,

23:49.428 --> 23:53.839
he's got an incentive not
to tell anything to anybody.

23:53.923 --> 23:55.924
<i>- Carmen Keller brings
more to the table</i>

23:56.009 --> 23:58.177
<i>than just
an extra pair of hands.</i>

23:58.261 --> 24:00.345
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:00.430 --> 24:05.359
- He had a job as a pass runner
for the educational department.

24:05.444 --> 24:06.777
<i>- As a pass runner,</i>

24:06.936 --> 24:09.196
<i>Carmen is given access to places</i>

24:09.355 --> 24:12.024
<i>and allowed to wander the
prison without much oversight.</i>

24:12.108 --> 24:16.361
<i>This means he has time to dig
and can provide passes</i>

24:16.446 --> 24:19.039
<i>for the other inmates
to get them out of their jobs</i>

24:19.199 --> 24:21.625
<i>and cells when need be.</i>

24:21.710 --> 24:23.702
<i>While the three men dig
the tunnel,</i>

24:23.786 --> 24:25.954
<i>Nuno is planning ahead.</i>

24:26.039 --> 24:29.884
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:29.968 --> 24:31.877
<i>And for the getaway,</i>

24:31.970 --> 24:35.547
<i>he will need to add
a fourth team member,</i>

24:35.640 --> 24:37.216
<i>George Conard.</i>

24:37.300 --> 24:43.138
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:43.223 --> 24:45.399
<i>George Conard is
a convicted killer</i>

24:45.558 --> 24:47.476
<i>serving a life sentence.</i>

24:47.560 --> 24:49.236
<i>- George Conard is
from Pittsburg,</i>

24:49.321 --> 24:50.738
and he's got contacts
on the outside

24:50.822 --> 24:53.157
that can provide us
with a getaway car

24:53.316 --> 24:55.234
once we get to the other side
of the wall.

24:55.318 --> 24:58.070
<i>- Conard is essential
to arranging local connections</i>

24:58.154 --> 25:00.247
<i>once they escape the prison
so that Nuno</i>

25:00.332 --> 25:02.666
<i>and his team can travel
to Texas.</i>

25:02.751 --> 25:05.410
<i>From there, they plan
to leave the country</i>

25:05.495 --> 25:07.579
<i>and go their separate ways.</i>

25:07.664 --> 25:09.081
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:09.165 --> 25:12.501
<i>With Conard, the four-member
team is able to dig faster</i>

25:12.594 --> 25:15.420
<i>than they ever have before.</i>

25:15.505 --> 25:17.506
<i>- We are trying to get as many
shifts in as possible.</i>

25:17.599 --> 25:19.174
<i>Keller can get away
in the morning,</i>

25:19.259 --> 25:23.095
and I can also sneak away
in the morning sometimes.

25:23.179 --> 25:25.105
<i>But most of the time,
it's Carmen and Kevin</i>

25:25.265 --> 25:26.524
<i>in the afternoon.</i>

25:26.608 --> 25:30.352
<i>- After four weeks,
they have dug 14 feet down</i>

25:30.436 --> 25:33.781
<i>and 30 feet across
under the access road,</i>

25:33.940 --> 25:38.026
<i>putting them somewhere right
below the wall's foundation.</i>

25:38.119 --> 25:40.538
<i>Although they are moving
quicker now,</i>

25:40.622 --> 25:43.115
<i>there's always the danger of
being caught red-handed.</i>

25:43.199 --> 25:50.289
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:50.373 --> 25:52.541
- One day, I put him
in the tunnel, lock him in,

25:52.625 --> 25:54.552
and I go
to the Chow Hole to eat.

25:54.636 --> 25:56.637
<i>While I'm in
the Chow Hole eating,</i>

25:56.721 --> 25:58.389
the alarms go off.

25:58.473 --> 25:59.965
<i>They blow the horn three times.</i>

26:00.058 --> 26:02.893
[horn blares]

26:02.978 --> 26:06.313
<i>- In December of '96,
shortly after noon,</i>

26:06.398 --> 26:09.233
<i>an inmate stabbed two officers.</i>

26:09.392 --> 26:11.393
From that,
we did a general alarm to get

26:11.477 --> 26:13.988
<i>all the inmates
back into their cellblocks</i>

26:14.147 --> 26:15.823
<i>in a general lockdown.</i>

26:15.907 --> 26:18.650
<i>- They locked the Chow Hole.
I'm locked in there.</i>

26:18.735 --> 26:20.819
<i>And, obviously, the first thing</i>

26:20.903 --> 26:21.829
<i>what I'm thinking now is,</i>

26:21.988 --> 26:23.080
<i>"I gotta go
get these guys out."</i>

26:23.239 --> 26:25.583
<i>This prison's
gonna be locked down,</i>

26:25.667 --> 26:26.825
<i>and they have no way
out of there.</i>

26:26.918 --> 26:29.420
[horn blares]

26:29.504 --> 26:32.164
<i>- Mr. Pontes knew if he didn't
get them out of there</i>

26:32.248 --> 26:34.666
right away, the jig was up.

26:34.751 --> 26:37.002
- If they were found out
digging that tunnel,

26:37.095 --> 26:39.004
they would have went
to the Hole for a lot of years.

26:39.097 --> 26:40.514
<i>A lot of years.</i>

26:40.599 --> 26:42.090
- Let's go, let's go!

26:42.175 --> 26:44.351
<i>- Nuno Pontes is going to
have to think fast</i>

26:44.436 --> 26:47.346
<i>if he's going to get the guys
safely out of the tunnel</i>

26:47.430 --> 26:50.024
<i>without anyone knowing
what they were up to.</i>

26:50.108 --> 26:53.277
<i>If he can't figure it out,
the escape is over,</i>

26:53.361 --> 26:55.195
<i>and they will all rot
in the Hole</i>

26:55.355 --> 26:57.281
<i>for many, many years.</i>

27:03.121 --> 27:06.698
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:06.791 --> 27:10.294
<i>- For the last year,
four men have been furiously</i>

27:10.378 --> 27:12.713
<i>planning and working
towards a daring escape</i>

27:12.797 --> 27:17.292
<i>from Pennsylvania's infamous
Western Penitentiary.</i>

27:17.377 --> 27:20.971
<i>Their plans are
on the brink of collapse</i>

27:21.130 --> 27:24.883
<i>as two prison guards
have been stabbed,</i>

27:24.967 --> 27:28.637
<i>sending the prison
into lockdown mode.</i>

27:28.721 --> 27:32.483
Carmen Keller
and Kevin Billingsley

27:32.642 --> 27:36.070
are underground,
digging the escape tunnel.

27:36.154 --> 27:38.405
They can't hear
the lockdown alarm

27:38.564 --> 27:39.990
blaring at the surface.

27:40.075 --> 27:44.403
Mastermind Nuno Pontes
has to think fast

27:44.496 --> 27:46.905
because if they don't
get back to their cells

27:46.989 --> 27:51.835
for head count, the entire
escape plot is done for,

27:51.994 --> 27:53.912
and they'll all spend years
in the Hole.

27:53.996 --> 27:56.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:56.174 --> 27:57.833
<i>- I could have walked away.</i>

27:57.917 --> 28:01.261
They would have been locked
in there.

28:01.421 --> 28:03.263
That wouldn't have been neither
the smart nor the right thing

28:03.348 --> 28:05.507
to do.

28:05.591 --> 28:08.185
<i>- Nuno Pontes asks
two fellow inmates</i>

28:08.344 --> 28:10.604
<i>to create a disturbance
as they're walking back</i>

28:10.689 --> 28:12.681
<i>to their cells
so he can slip off.</i>

28:12.765 --> 28:14.349
- [whispers] Now.

28:14.434 --> 28:17.352
[people shouting]

28:17.437 --> 28:24.535
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:24.619 --> 28:27.612
<i>- His plan works,
and the guard doesn't realize</i>

28:27.706 --> 28:30.207
<i>he's missing.</i>

28:30.366 --> 28:32.534
<i>But Nuno isn't in the clear yet.</i>

28:32.618 --> 28:34.712
<i>He still has to get
into the crawl space</i>

28:34.796 --> 28:37.539
<i>and be locked in so the guards
don't notice anything</i>

28:37.623 --> 28:38.874
<i>out of place.</i>

28:38.958 --> 28:41.218
<i>And to do that,
he's going to need the help</i>

28:41.302 --> 28:42.469
<i>of another inmate,</i>

28:42.554 --> 28:46.306
<i>one who isn't aware
of the escape plan.</i>

28:46.391 --> 28:49.718
<i>- I grabbed this guy, Tree,
and I said, come with me.</i>

28:49.802 --> 28:51.803
I didn't necessarily want
to let anybody else know,

28:51.896 --> 28:53.313
but I have no choice.

28:53.398 --> 28:56.734
I tell Tree, here's this key.
Lock this door behind me.

28:56.818 --> 28:58.643
Come back in ten minutes
and let me out.

28:58.728 --> 29:02.314
And that was--that was
a very tense moment

29:02.407 --> 29:04.483
<i>'cause I have no idea
if this guy's gonna do it.</i>

29:04.567 --> 29:08.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:08.321 --> 29:10.071
<i>I started to go through
the crawl space.</i>

29:10.165 --> 29:12.073
<i>Kevin and Carmen are coming.</i>

29:12.158 --> 29:13.417
For some reason,
they had a sense

29:13.576 --> 29:14.826
that something wasn't right,
so they were coming out

29:14.919 --> 29:16.253
of the tunnel.

29:16.337 --> 29:17.254
And I tell them,
"Look, we gotta go.

29:17.338 --> 29:19.998
There's a lockdown
in progress."

29:20.082 --> 29:22.926
<i>We go back to the exit.</i>

29:23.085 --> 29:24.928
<i>- Nuno and the escape team fear</i>

29:25.013 --> 29:27.097
<i>Tree won't come back
to let them out.</i>

29:27.182 --> 29:31.009
<i>If he doesn't come back, the
next person to open that door</i>

29:31.093 --> 29:32.928
<i>will be one of the guards,</i>

29:33.012 --> 29:37.015
<i>guaranteeing them all years
in solitary.</i>

29:37.099 --> 29:41.111
<i>In their minds,
there's only one question,</i>

29:41.196 --> 29:43.688
<i>"Who's going to open
the door next?"</i>

29:43.782 --> 29:47.025
<i>Tree or the guards?</i>

29:47.109 --> 29:50.704
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:50.789 --> 29:56.126
<i>Thankfully, Tree pulls through
and opens the door.</i>

29:56.211 --> 29:58.537
- And so we went to our blocks,
and that was it.

29:58.621 --> 30:01.039
It was by the skin
of the teeth, as they say.

30:01.123 --> 30:04.709
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:04.794 --> 30:07.712
<i>- The team's close call
creates a strong bond,</i>

30:07.806 --> 30:11.225
<i>and they resolve to finish
the tunnel even faster.</i>

30:11.309 --> 30:12.559
- From then on,

30:12.718 --> 30:14.636
they were much more willing
to do whatever I said

30:14.729 --> 30:16.146
<i>'cause they just
couldn't believe</i>

30:16.231 --> 30:18.890
<i>that I actually went there
and told Tree to lock me in.</i>

30:18.975 --> 30:20.818
<i>'Cause, in essence, whatever
fate they were gonna suffer,</i>

30:20.902 --> 30:22.394
<i>I was gonna suffer.</i>

30:22.478 --> 30:24.738
<i>- Meanwhile,
Nuno's working on the plan</i>

30:24.897 --> 30:28.400
<i>for what happens once they
leave the prison walls behind.</i>

30:28.484 --> 30:32.079
- So Conard is supposed to have
gotten somebody to be there

30:32.163 --> 30:33.405
with a car for us.

30:33.498 --> 30:35.574
But he's not coming through,
so we need somebody

30:35.658 --> 30:37.742
that knows how to steal a car.

30:37.827 --> 30:40.495
<i>And none of us has any
experience with stealing cars.</i>

30:40.580 --> 30:42.840
<i>Kevin, he says, "Look, there's
this kid that's a car thief.</i>

30:42.924 --> 30:44.833
<i>He can hotwire
a car very quickly.</i>

30:44.917 --> 30:48.003
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:48.087 --> 30:51.673
<i>- Andrew Heim is serving
a 4-to 15-year sentence</i>

30:51.757 --> 30:54.259
<i>for theft and assault offenses.</i>

30:54.352 --> 30:58.346
- I don't really know Andrew,
but we do have this problem.

30:58.431 --> 30:59.347
- There was certainly a risk

30:59.432 --> 31:01.191
with Nuno adding
additional members

31:01.276 --> 31:03.110
because the more people
that know stuff,

31:03.194 --> 31:05.437
the more people that can tell.

31:05.521 --> 31:07.030
<i>- Andrew Heim is
the fifth member</i>

31:07.115 --> 31:08.282
<i>added to the team</i>

31:08.441 --> 31:11.285
<i>just as the tunnel is
nearing completion.</i>

31:11.369 --> 31:13.778
<i>But he's not
the only new addition.</i>

31:13.863 --> 31:17.791
<i>Nuno brings on
an unlikely sixth member,</i>

31:17.876 --> 31:19.451
<i>Thomas Berkelbaugh.</i>

31:19.535 --> 31:23.547
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:23.631 --> 31:26.207
<i>Berkelbaugh has
a long history of robberies</i>

31:26.292 --> 31:29.628
<i>and is serving
a 10-to 20-year sentence.</i>

31:29.721 --> 31:32.639
- Berkelbaugh is a little bit
of a different duck,

31:32.798 --> 31:34.391
as far as the escape goes.

31:34.550 --> 31:37.811
<i>He had very little role
to play in it.</i>

31:37.896 --> 31:40.564
<i>He and Pontes were friends.</i>

31:40.648 --> 31:42.733
<i>They decided to take him along</i>

31:42.817 --> 31:44.818
<i>because they felt sorry for him</i>

31:44.903 --> 31:47.145
<i>that he was gonna go blind.</i>

31:47.229 --> 31:50.649
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:50.733 --> 31:52.910
<i>- There are now six inmates</i>

31:52.994 --> 31:54.828
<i>in on the escape.</i>

31:54.987 --> 31:57.572
<i>The team is complete.</i>

31:57.657 --> 32:00.158
<i>- When you look at these six,
they live in different areas,</i>

32:00.242 --> 32:01.919
<i>they work in different areas,</i>

32:02.078 --> 32:06.840
<i>their age groups
are from 30 to 65.</i>

32:06.999 --> 32:10.177
There's not a lot of other
things that tie them together,

32:10.261 --> 32:13.180
other than the goal
of doing this escape.

32:13.264 --> 32:14.589
<i>- The prisoners
have been tunneling</i>

32:14.674 --> 32:16.841
<i>for four months.</i>

32:16.935 --> 32:18.685
<i>But the most difficult part
of breaking out</i>

32:18.844 --> 32:21.513
<i>still hangs over their heads,</i>

32:21.606 --> 32:25.525
<i>digging straight up 14 feet
to reach the floor</i>

32:25.610 --> 32:28.278
<i>of the industrial warehouse.</i>

32:28.437 --> 32:30.021
- Now you're actually
excavating the dirt

32:30.114 --> 32:31.272
above your head.

32:31.357 --> 32:34.117
If you hit any kind
of unstable condition,

32:34.202 --> 32:36.954
then you're gonna get
a major collapse.

32:37.038 --> 32:38.705
- I was the only one
crazy enough

32:38.864 --> 32:39.864
to do that sort of thing.

32:39.958 --> 32:41.708
<i>And the last
bit of dirt came down,</i>

32:41.867 --> 32:44.711
<i>and this rush of air came in.</i>

32:44.796 --> 32:46.621
This vacuum of "Whoo!"

32:46.714 --> 32:48.707
<i>The tunnel filled with air.</i>

32:48.791 --> 32:51.885
[breathing heavily]

32:51.970 --> 32:56.297
<i>- Freedom is
so close they can feel it,</i>

32:56.391 --> 32:59.050
<i>but their tunnel isn't complete.</i>

32:59.135 --> 33:03.146
<i>The last and most
difficult step is next,</i>

33:03.231 --> 33:05.223
<i>breaking through the warehouse's</i>

33:05.307 --> 33:07.976
<i>reinforced concrete floor.</i>

33:08.060 --> 33:11.896
<i>To do that,
they're going to need tools.</i>

33:11.981 --> 33:16.660
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:16.819 --> 33:19.738
- I have keys that I made
for the engineer's office

33:19.831 --> 33:21.906
and for the cabinets,
that's where there's tools.

33:21.991 --> 33:25.744
We wait until night.

33:25.828 --> 33:29.330
<i>I get a hammer drill,
and an hydraulic jack.</i>

33:29.415 --> 33:31.499
<i>We took those tools down
into the tunnel,</i>

33:31.584 --> 33:34.586
<i>we drilled a bunch of holes
in the concrete</i>

33:34.670 --> 33:36.004
<i>to weaken the concrete.</i>

33:36.097 --> 33:37.180
<i>And then we made a little indent</i>

33:37.265 --> 33:38.348
<i>on the cement wall,</i>

33:38.507 --> 33:39.933
<i>put the hydraulic jack
against that,</i>

33:40.092 --> 33:41.509
<i>and then we just pump.</i>

33:41.594 --> 33:44.438
<i>[drill hammers]</i>

33:44.597 --> 33:48.433
- So they crank this jack
till it literally broke through

33:48.517 --> 33:50.360
the concrete floor.

33:50.445 --> 33:52.612
And then they use this
reciprocating saw

33:52.772 --> 33:54.606
<i>to cut through the rebar</i>

33:54.690 --> 33:56.775
<i>and create an opening that
allowed them to have access.</i>

33:56.859 --> 34:00.537
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:00.696 --> 34:04.282
<i>- They came up near
a mechanical room</i>

34:04.375 --> 34:05.625
<i>for two reasons.</i>

34:05.710 --> 34:08.286
<i>There's a lot of noise there
that would cover</i>

34:08.370 --> 34:10.714
their noise that they would make

34:10.873 --> 34:12.540
when they're breaking
through the floor.

34:12.625 --> 34:15.293
<i>And it's in the very back
of the warehouse,</i>

34:15.377 --> 34:19.973
quite a ways from where any
staff would be at, normally.

34:20.132 --> 34:23.643
<i>- It's a bold risk to
leave the tunnel exit exposed,</i>

34:23.803 --> 34:26.137
<i>but they have no choice.</i>

34:26.222 --> 34:30.475
<i>They all can't get there
until the morning.</i>

34:30.559 --> 34:34.145
<i>They just have to pray
that no one will find it</i>

34:34.230 --> 34:36.147
<i>before they can leave.</i>

34:36.232 --> 34:37.908
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:43.239 --> 34:44.915
- At Pittsburg's
notorious Western Pen,

34:44.999 --> 34:47.918
it's almost go time.

34:48.002 --> 34:50.411
Nuno Pontes
and his coconspirators

34:50.496 --> 34:53.081
have completed
their tunnel to freedom.

34:53.174 --> 34:56.676
Now they wait for dawn to break

34:56.761 --> 35:01.014
so that
all six of them can escape.

35:01.173 --> 35:03.174
<i>- I was awake all night.</i>

35:03.267 --> 35:05.343
That is the first and
only time during this project

35:05.427 --> 35:07.938
when I confronted the enormity
of what's going on.

35:08.097 --> 35:10.273
<i>I'm responsible
for these guys with me,</i>

35:10.432 --> 35:12.100
<i>and all sorts of things
can go wrong.</i>

35:12.184 --> 35:13.860
<i>So I remember being in the cell</i>

35:13.945 --> 35:15.937
and just shaking uncontrollably.

35:16.021 --> 35:23.027
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:23.112 --> 35:25.530
<i>- Dawn eventually comes.</i>

35:25.614 --> 35:27.031
<i>It's time.</i>

35:27.116 --> 35:29.376
<i>- All six of the inmates were
up early that morning.</i>

35:29.535 --> 35:33.046
Most of them left their cells
sometime between 6:00 and 6:30.

35:33.131 --> 35:34.965
<i>- Keller was a pass runner.</i>

35:35.124 --> 35:38.718
<i>He got us a bunch of blank
early call passes.</i>

35:38.878 --> 35:40.461
<i>These are passes that get
you out of your cell early</i>

35:40.555 --> 35:42.722
before they open for the day.

35:42.807 --> 35:45.383
- They converged, and
they started to work their way

35:45.467 --> 35:46.718
through the tunnel.

35:46.802 --> 35:52.056
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:52.141 --> 35:53.483
<i>- Conard had never been there,</i>

35:53.642 --> 35:56.069
<i>Andrew Heim had never been
there,</i>

35:56.154 --> 35:59.823
<i>Berkelbaugh had never been
there, so Kevin went first,</i>

35:59.907 --> 36:02.659
<i>and I went last to make sure
nobody would turn around</i>

36:02.743 --> 36:05.737
<i>and potentially
give the thing away.</i>

36:05.821 --> 36:07.164
<i>- Making it through the tunnel</i>

36:07.248 --> 36:11.918
<i>would be challenging,
even for the most athletic.</i>

36:12.003 --> 36:15.255
<i>Nuno worries that they
may not all be able to claw</i>

36:15.414 --> 36:17.832
<i>their way to freedom.</i>

36:17.917 --> 36:19.593
<i>- Berkelbaugh is right
in front of me.</i>

36:19.677 --> 36:21.085
<i>His prosthetic eye came out.</i>

36:21.170 --> 36:23.922
- Augh!

36:24.006 --> 36:26.016
<i>- He just felt his way around
and found it.</i>

36:26.100 --> 36:28.676
<i>You know, it was
one of those surreal moments.</i>

36:28.761 --> 36:32.931
"I lost my eye." [chuckles]
Well, it happens.

36:33.015 --> 36:39.863
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:51.375 --> 36:55.036
<i>- Amazingly, all six
make it out of the tunnel.</i>

36:55.120 --> 36:57.214
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:57.298 --> 36:59.132
<i>- Finally, we are all
in this room in the warehouse.</i>

36:59.217 --> 37:01.709
We change clothes.

37:01.794 --> 37:04.721
- At the time, the prison
allowed civilian clothes.

37:04.805 --> 37:07.131
This was part of a prisoner's
bill of rights.

37:07.216 --> 37:11.394
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:11.553 --> 37:13.313
<i>- Even with
their civilian clothes on,</i>

37:13.472 --> 37:17.317
<i>they need to figure out a way
to get out of the warehouse,</i>

37:17.476 --> 37:19.560
<i>and there is a catch.</i>

37:19.645 --> 37:21.571
<i>A guard is stationed on the wall</i>

37:21.730 --> 37:24.482
<i>directly above the exit
to the street.</i>

37:24.566 --> 37:26.326
<i>- Turns out,
the door can just be opened,</i>

37:26.485 --> 37:29.579
<i>so I go out there first
to see what needed to be done.</i>

37:29.664 --> 37:31.748
<i>The guard is there,
and he's looking at me.</i>

37:31.832 --> 37:34.334
I come back in, and I say,
"Look, the guard is sitting

37:34.418 --> 37:37.078
"out there on the wall,
so you guys just remain calm.

37:37.171 --> 37:38.830
I'm gonna say something
to him."

37:38.923 --> 37:41.582
<i>We have street clothes,
we have hardhats.</i>

37:41.667 --> 37:43.927
<i>- Because it is outside
the secure perimeter,</i>

37:44.011 --> 37:46.337
<i>anyone that you would see
there, you would think was</i>

37:46.422 --> 37:48.673
<i>either working as
a maintenance crew.</i>

37:48.757 --> 37:49.841
<i>No one would think</i>

37:49.925 --> 37:52.352
<i>that inmates are coming
from that area</i>

37:52.436 --> 37:54.345
and escaping the institution.

37:54.430 --> 37:58.358
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:58.517 --> 38:00.685
<i>- So we all walk out.</i>

38:00.778 --> 38:02.445
<i>The guard looks down at us,
and I look up at him</i>

38:02.604 --> 38:04.614
<i>and waved at him,
and he waved at us.</i>

38:04.773 --> 38:08.276
<i>And we went out the door
onto the street.</i>

38:08.360 --> 38:11.195
<i>The exhilaration
was overwhelming.</i>

38:11.289 --> 38:13.531
<i>The air felt different,
the light felt different.</i>

38:13.624 --> 38:14.958
<i>Everything.</i>

38:15.042 --> 38:16.626
There's something
supernatural about it,

38:16.785 --> 38:18.703
it's just unbelievable
'cause, I guess,

38:18.787 --> 38:20.046
until the very last minute,
you don't think

38:20.131 --> 38:21.205
it's gonna go through.

38:21.290 --> 38:24.459
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:24.552 --> 38:28.212
We are free, but not scot-free.

38:28.297 --> 38:30.548
I mean, obviously,
now is the hard part.

38:30.641 --> 38:33.143
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:33.302 --> 38:34.561
- As soon as they got
outside the prison,

38:34.645 --> 38:37.647
they stole a car,
piled into that car.

38:37.732 --> 38:41.059
[engine revs]

38:41.143 --> 38:43.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:43.479 --> 38:46.397
<i>- What the guards did not
realize is</i>

38:46.490 --> 38:49.650
<i>all of them had escaped
through the tunnel,</i>

38:49.735 --> 38:52.904
probably around
8:00 in the morning.

38:52.988 --> 38:55.999
<i>And it wasn't until
the 10:00 head count</i>

38:56.083 --> 38:59.577
<i>that the institution realized
there was a breakout.</i>

38:59.661 --> 39:01.671
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:01.756 --> 39:04.165
<i>- The Pittsburg Six
may have just executed</i>

39:04.249 --> 39:07.001
<i>the perfect prison escape.</i>

39:07.086 --> 39:08.595
<i>They have a two-hour head start</i>

39:08.679 --> 39:10.755
<i>on the authorities.</i>

39:10.839 --> 39:12.182
<i>But now they are faced</i>

39:12.341 --> 39:15.435
<i>with their biggest challenge
so far.</i>

39:15.519 --> 39:17.762
<i>Will they survive on the outside</i>

39:17.846 --> 39:19.356
<i>without being apprehended?</i>

39:25.363 --> 39:27.021
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:27.106 --> 39:30.608
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:30.692 --> 39:33.111
<i>- Six inmates
at Western Penitentiary,</i>

39:33.204 --> 39:36.539
<i>led by Nuno Pontes,
have tunneled their way</i>

39:36.624 --> 39:39.117
<i>out of the run down
and dangerous prison.</i>

39:39.201 --> 39:41.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:41.954 --> 39:45.289
<i>The six are now on the run,
hoping they won't get caught.</i>

39:45.383 --> 39:46.633
- I understood.

39:46.792 --> 39:48.543
I knew it was much more likely
for me to get caught

39:48.636 --> 39:50.044
if I were with them
than without them,

39:50.129 --> 39:53.723
but the consequence of leaving
them to their own devices,

39:53.882 --> 39:55.308
somebody might have gotten
seriously hurt,

39:55.393 --> 39:56.893
and I'm the one that made
the escape happen,

39:57.052 --> 39:58.469
so it would have been
my responsibility.

39:58.562 --> 40:00.647
- The fact that there were six
of them together

40:00.731 --> 40:03.233
compounded the likelihood
that we were going

40:03.317 --> 40:04.818
to catch up with them.

40:04.902 --> 40:08.563
- They became known
as the Pittsburg Six.

40:08.647 --> 40:10.824
- We were gonna go to Texas,
get our IDs,

40:10.983 --> 40:13.067
<i>go from Texas to Mexico,</i>

40:13.152 --> 40:15.653
<i>and then from Mexico
onto South America,</i>

40:15.737 --> 40:17.989
<i>and then from there, everybody
could go their own way.</i>

40:18.073 --> 40:21.334
<i>- The six travel
undetected to Pasadena, Texas.</i>

40:21.419 --> 40:23.586
<i>There, they hide in a hotel</i>

40:23.745 --> 40:26.080
<i>while waiting
for falsified documents</i>

40:26.165 --> 40:27.498
<i>so they can leave the country.</i>

40:27.583 --> 40:32.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:32.430 --> 40:35.506
- It wasn't until the first
substantial lead came

40:35.599 --> 40:37.091
<i>on day six.</i>

